{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "TroposphericChemistrySystem",
        "description": "Combined tropospheric chemistry diagnostic system (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Chapter 6) — couples three photochemical subsystems into a comprehensive steady-state diagnostic model of tropospheric photochemistry: OH production from O3 photolysis (§6.1), the NOx photochemical cycle (§6.2), and CO oxidation chemistry (§6.3). Migrated from GasChem.jl@8c12c048 src/combined_system.jl:54 (`TroposphericChemistrySystem` @component). The three subsystems — `oh` (OHProduction), `nox` (NOxPhotochemistry), `co` (COOxidation) — are inlined verbatim (ESS spec §4.7 subsystem composition) from their already-migrated standalone .esm files; the parent supplies 14 coupling equations feeding the shared species (O3, NO, NO2, OH, HO2, CO, CH3O2, H2O, M, O2) into the subsystems and 9 combined-diagnostic equations (total/net O3 production, ozone production efficiency, NOx loss rate, HOx chain length). Purely algebraic — a steady-state diagnostic system with no time derivatives. SI units throughout (m^-3 for concentrations, m^3/s for bimolecular rate constants).",
        "tags": [
            "gaschem",
            "tropospheric",
            "photochemistry",
            "combined-system",
            "coupled-subsystems",
            "seinfeld-pandis",
            "diagnostics"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "GasChem.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-ui1r)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H. and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition. Wiley. Chapter 6 (Chemistry of the Atmosphere) — Section 6.1 OH production, Section 6.2 NOx photochemical cycle, Section 6.3 CO oxidation chemistry."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "TroposphericChemistrySystem": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H. and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition. Wiley. Chapter 6.",
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/combined_system.jl:54\n\nUpstream `TroposphericChemistrySystem` is an MTK `@component` that composes three subsystems via `System(eqs, t; systems = [oh_sys, nox_sys, co_sys], name)` — oh_sys = OHProduction(name=:oh), nox_sys = NOxPhotochemistry(name=:nox), co_sys = COOxidation(name=:co) — and adds 14 coupling equations and 9 combined-diagnostic equations. It declares 2 `@parameters` (k_CH4_OH, k_CH3O2_NO), 10 input `@variables` (O3, NO, NO2, OH, HO2, CO, CH3O2, H2O, M, O2 — all m^-3) and 9 output `@variables` (NOx, HOx, RO2, P_O3_total, L_O3_total, P_O3_net, OPE, chain_length, L_NOx). The upstream tests compile it with `mtkcompile(sys; inputs=[...10 species...])` and solve a `NonlinearProblem` — the whole system is algebraic (no `D(·)`).\n\nMigration approach (ESS spec §4.7 subsystem composition): the three subsystems are inlined verbatim under `subsystems` as `oh`/`nox`/`co`, copied (variables + equations) from the already-migrated standalone files components/gaschem/oh_production.esm (OHProduction), components/gaschem/nox_photochemistry/photochemistry.esm (NOxPhotochemistry) and components/gaschem/co_oxidation/co_oxidation.esm (COOxidation). This mirrors the inline-subsystem precedent set by components/gaschem/radiation/radiation_fundamentals.esm (the other migrated `coupling.couple` @component) and keeps the combined model faithful to the upstream `systems=[...]` hierarchical structure.\n\nInput re-typing: each subsystem's input @variables — standalone typed `parameter` because they have no defining equation within the component (oh: O3/H2O/M; nox: NO/NO2/O3/O2/M; co: CO/OH/HO2/NO/NO2/O3) — are re-typed `state` here. In the combined model they DO have a defining equation: the parent coupling equation `<sub>.<input> ~ <input>` binds each to the corresponding combined-system input. A `parameter` cannot appear on an equation LHS, so the re-type is required; the standalone files remain unchanged. The 24 subsystem rate-constant parameters and the two `two` stoichiometric constants stay `parameter`.\n\nCoupling references: the 14 coupling equations and the diagnostic equations reference subsystem variables by their fully-qualified path from the top-level model name (spec §4.6), e.g. `TroposphericChemistrySystem.co.k_HO2_NO`. After flatten (earthsci_toolkit.flatten, spec §4.7.5) every variable is dot-namespaced by its owning system and the coupling equations join the subsystem inputs to the combined inputs.\n\nDangling parameter: `k_CH4_OH` is declared verbatim from upstream but referenced by no equation — the upstream @component declares it for the combined system's documented Section 6.4 methane scope but `TroposphericChemistrySystem` does not wire methane oxidation into its equation set. Preserved as a declared parameter for fidelity.\n\nSystem classification: purely algebraic — every equation is an `~` relation with no `D(·)` operator, so the flattened system is a steady-state diagnostic (NonlinearProblem upstream). The trajectory is constant in time; inline tests sample at t=0 over time_span [0, 1], mirroring the sibling observed-only/algebraic ESM files (oh_production.esm, co_oxidation.esm, photochemistry.esm, typical.esm).\n\nTolerance (model-level rel=1e-10 / abs=1e-12): the flattened system is a feed-forward algebraic cascade (combined inputs -> subsystem diagnostics -> combined diagnostics) of small expression trees; the canonical runner resolves it without iterative error accumulation. rel=1e-10 matches the three inlined subsystems' own model tolerance and is far tighter than the upstream tests' rtol=1e-6 combined-diagnostic bounds; abs=1e-12 gates the exact-IEEE-754-zero outputs that arise in the term-isolation test (HO2_ss=0 when CO=0).\n\nUpstream test reproduction (GasChem.jl test/test_combined_system.jl): the inline tests reproduce every numeric upstream testitem — `NOx = NO + NO2` / `HOx = OH + HO2` (NOx, HOx, RO2 sums), `O3 Production Diagnostics` and `O3 Production Budget Consistency` (P_O3_total, L_O3_total, P_O3_net), `NOx Loss Rate` (L_NOx = k_OH_NO2·OH·NO2), `OPE Calculation` (OPE = P_O3_total/L_NOx), `OH/NOx/CO Coupling` (oh/nox/co subsystem outputs), and `NOx-VOC Regime Differences` (Urban and Remote presets). The purely-structural upstream testitems (`Structural Verification`, `Subsystem Composition`, `Subsystem Variable Access`) are satisfied by the file structure — the 3 named subsystems and the diagnostic variable names — and are not expressible as numeric simulate assertions. Four further tests beyond the upstream suite isolate the CO term (CO=0), the O3 linearity of the loss budget (O3 doubled), the high-HO2 regime, and the low-NO regime.\n\nExamples: this file declares no `examples` block. The example-plot renderer (tools/render_example_plots.py) resolves algebraic (non-dynamic) models with an equation-resolution plan that operates on the top-level model alone and does not descend into `subsystems`; the combined-diagnostic equations reference subsystem variables by fully-qualified path and are therefore unresolvable by the renderer's algebraic path. This mirrors the sibling subsystem-composed `coupling.couple` migration components/gaschem/radiation/radiation_fundamentals.esm, which likewise declares no examples. The inline `tests` block provides the full numeric verification in lieu of example plots.\n\nAll inline-test expected values are the canonical ESS Python runner output: earthsci_toolkit.simulation.simulate(cse=False, rtol=1e-10, atol=1e-12) — the same runner and settings as the CI gate tools/run_esm_inline_tests.py. SI units throughout."
            },
            "variables": {
                "O3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1e+18,
                    "description": "Ozone concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "NO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2500000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Nitric oxide concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "NO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e+16,
                    "description": "Nitrogen dioxide concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "OH": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Hydroxyl radical concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "HO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 100000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Hydroperoxy radical concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "CO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e+18,
                    "description": "Carbon monoxide concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "CH3O2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 100000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Methylperoxy radical concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "H2O": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 4e+23,
                    "description": "Water vapor concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "M": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e+25,
                    "description": "Total air number density concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "O2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 5.25e+24,
                    "description": "Molecular oxygen concentration — combined-system input species, supplied externally and fed into the oh/nox/co subsystems by the coupling equations. Default is the TypicalConditions mid-latitude lower-troposphere value (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6)."
                },
                "k_CH4_OH": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 6.3437334324972315e-21,
                    "description": "CH4 + OH rate constant — 2.45e-12·exp(-1775/298)·1e-6 cm^3/molec/s converted to m^3/s (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Table 6.1 reaction 1, evaluated at T=298 K). Declared verbatim from the upstream @parameters block for the combined system's documented Section 6.4 methane-oxidation scope; no TroposphericChemistrySystem equation references it (methane chemistry is not wired into this diagnostic model)."
                },
                "k_CH3O2_NO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 7.699999999999999e-18,
                    "description": "CH3O2 + NO rate constant — 7.7e-12 cm^3/molec/s converted to m^3/s (×1e-6). Drives the CH3O2+NO ozone-production channel in the P_O3_total diagnostic."
                },
                "NOx": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "description": "Total NOx = NO + NO2."
                },
                "HOx": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "description": "Total HOx = OH + HO2."
                },
                "RO2": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "description": "Total organic peroxy radicals (simplified to CH3O2 only)."
                },
                "P_O3_total": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Total O3 production rate — sum of the HO2+NO (co subsystem rate constant) and CH3O2+NO peroxy-radical ozone-production channels."
                },
                "L_O3_total": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Total O3 loss rate — sum of NO+O3 (nox subsystem rate constant), OH+O3 and HO2+O3 (co subsystem rate constants)."
                },
                "P_O3_net": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Net O3 tendency = P_O3_total - L_O3_total."
                },
                "OPE": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Ozone production efficiency = P_O3_total / L_NOx (dimensionless) — O3 molecules produced per NOx molecule consumed."
                },
                "chain_length": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "HOx chain length (dimensionless), re-exposed at the combined level from the co subsystem's chain_length diagnostic."
                },
                "L_NOx": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "NOx loss rate (mainly HNO3 formation) = k_OH_NO2·OH·NO2, using the co subsystem rate constant."
                }
            },
            "subsystems": {
                "oh": {
                    "variables": {
                        "j_O3": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "s^-1",
                            "default": 6e-05,
                            "description": "O₃ photolysis rate producing O(¹D) at surface, solar zenith angle 0° (S&P Figure 4.15, Table B.1). The upstream default 6.0e-5 s⁻¹ is the noon-equatorial-surface canonical value; at other zenith angles and altitudes j_O₃ varies by factors of 10⁻²-10¹ — overridable for scenarios at higher altitudes (j_O₃ increases roughly 2-3× from surface to 12 km), higher latitudes (drops with sec(SZA)), or non-equatorial seasons. Downstream coupling: in the full TroposphericChemistrySystem this parameter is provided by the upstream FastJX or SuperFast photolysis subsystem via param_to_var coupling."
                        },
                        "k3_N2": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 2.6e-17,
                            "description": "O(¹D) + N₂ quenching rate constant (S&P Table B.1, IUPAC-recommended at 298 K). The upstream default 2.6e-17 m³/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 2.6e-11 cm³/molec/s — the canonical IUPAC-recommended bimolecular rate coefficient for O(¹D) + N₂ → O(³P) + N₂ at 298 K. Weakly temperature-dependent (k₃,N₂ ∝ exp(110/T) per IUPAC 2007 update — about 50% faster at 200 K than 298 K) but the upstream uses the temperature-independent 298 K value for the algebraic system. The two quenching channels (k₃_N₂, k₃_O₂) are weighted by their atmospheric mass fractions (f_N₂=0.78, f_O₂=0.21) to give the effective k₃_eff = 0.78·k₃_N₂ + 0.21·k₃_O₂ = 2.868e-17 m³/s used in the denominator of Eqs. 6.1 and 6.4."
                        },
                        "k3_O2": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 4e-17,
                            "description": "O(¹D) + O₂ quenching rate constant (S&P Table B.1, IUPAC-recommended at 298 K). The upstream default 4.0e-17 m³/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 4.0e-11 cm³/molec/s — the canonical bimolecular rate coefficient for O(¹D) + O₂ → O(³P) + O₂ at 298 K. About 1.5× faster than k₃_N₂ per molecule, but weighted by the smaller f_O₂=0.21 atmospheric mass fraction → the O₂ channel contributes 8.4e-18/2.868e-17 = 29% of k₃_eff while the N₂ channel contributes 71%. Weakly temperature-dependent (k₃,O₂ ∝ exp(55/T)) but the upstream uses the temperature-independent 298 K value."
                        },
                        "k4": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 2.2e-16,
                            "description": "O(¹D) + H₂O → 2 OH rate constant (S&P Table B.1, IUPAC-recommended at 298 K). The upstream default 2.2e-16 m³/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 2.2e-10 cm³/molec/s — the canonical bimolecular rate coefficient at 298 K. The OH-producing channel is ~5-10× faster per molecule than either quenching channel (k₄/k₃_N₂ ≈ 8.5, k₄/k₃_O₂ ≈ 5.5) — the reason H₂O is a far more efficient O(¹D) reaction partner per molecule than N₂ or O₂. But because [H₂O] / ([N₂]+[O₂]) ≈ 0.01-0.03 at typical surface RH, the absolute reaction-rate balance still favors quenching by ~5× (numerator vs denominator in the ε_OH formula): k₄[H₂O] = 2.2e-16·4e23 = 8.8e7 vs k₃_eff[M] = 2.868e-17·2.5e25 = 7.17e8, giving ε_OH ≈ 0.22 at S&P p. 207 conditions (about 1 in 5 O(¹D) atoms makes OH)."
                        },
                        "f_N2": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "1",
                            "default": 0.78,
                            "description": "Fraction of air number density that is N₂, dimensionless (S&P Page 1). The upstream default 0.78 reflects the well-mixed atmosphere composition where N₂ is the dominant species at all altitudes below the homopause (~100 km). f_N₂ + f_O₂ = 0.99 here (not exactly 1.0) — the residual 1% (Ar 0.93%, CO₂ 0.04%, plus trace gases) is treated as an 'inactive bath' that contributes negligible O(¹D) quenching at S&P's stated precision. Overridable for a hypothetical pure-N₂ atmosphere (f_N₂=1.0, f_O₂=0.0 → k₃_eff = k₃_N₂ = 2.6e-17) or for sensitivity studies on the trace-gas correction."
                        },
                        "f_O2": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "1",
                            "default": 0.21,
                            "description": "Fraction of air number density that is O₂, dimensionless (S&P Page 1). The upstream default 0.21 is the canonical well-mixed atmospheric O₂ fraction (more precisely 0.2095 by the standard dry-air composition table; the upstream uses 2-digit precision)."
                        },
                        "two": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "1",
                            "default": 2.0,
                            "description": "Stoichiometric factor: 2 OH radicals produced per O(¹D) + H₂O reaction (dimensionless). Preserved from upstream `@constants two = 2` per the rig convention (translating upstream `@constants` to fixed-default parameters so MTK's unit checker sees a named dimensionless quantity in the equation RHS — matches chapman.esm/gwp.esm/stefan_boltzmann.esm convention). The factor is hardwired by the O(¹D) + H₂O → 2 OH stoichiometry and not expected to change in routine use; overridable only for hypothetical alternate-stoichiometry sensitivity studies."
                        },
                        "O3": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 1e+18,
                            "description": "Ozone number density — the `oh` subsystem's O3 input. Re-typed from the standalone OHProduction component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model O3 is governed by the parent coupling equation `oh.O3 ~ O3`, which binds it to the combined-system input `O3`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "H2O": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 4e+23,
                            "description": "Water vapor number density — the `oh` subsystem's H2O input. Re-typed from the standalone OHProduction component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model H2O is governed by the parent coupling equation `oh.H2O ~ H2O`, which binds it to the combined-system input `H2O`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "M": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 2.5e+25,
                            "description": "Total air number density number density — the `oh` subsystem's M input. Re-typed from the standalone OHProduction component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model M is governed by the parent coupling equation `oh.M ~ M`, which binds it to the combined-system input `M`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "O1D": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "description": "Excited atomic oxygen O(¹D) steady-state number density [m⁻³] (Eq. 6.1). Algebraic balance between source j_O₃·O₃ and sinks k₃_eff·M + k₄·H₂O: O(¹D) = j_O₃·O₃ / (k₃_eff·M + k₄·H₂O). At S&P p. 207 default conditions O(¹D) ≈ 7.45e4 m⁻³ ≈ 7.45e-2 molec/cm³ — orders of magnitude smaller than ground-state O(³P) which itself is ~1e6-1e7 m⁻³ in the troposphere. The 'steady-state' label reflects the quasi-equilibrium assumption: O(¹D) lifetime is ~10⁻⁹ s (the inverse of k₃_eff·M ≈ 7e8 s⁻¹) which is many orders of magnitude shorter than any other tropospheric timescale, so the quasi-steady-state approximation is exact to within numerical precision. Linear in O₃ — doubling O₃ doubles O(¹D)."
                        },
                        "ε_OH": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "1",
                            "description": "OH yield: number of OH radicals produced per O(¹D) atom formed, dimensionless (Eq. 6.4). Algebraic ratio ε_OH = 2·k₄·H₂O / (k₃_eff·M + k₄·H₂O). Ranges from 0 (all O(¹D) quenched in pure-dry air → no OH made) to 2 (all O(¹D) reacts with H₂O → 2 OH per O(¹D) by stoichiometry of the 2-OH yield channel). At S&P p. 207 typical 50% RH default conditions ε_OH ≈ 0.22 (about 11% of O(¹D) reacts with H₂O, producing 22% as many OH as O(¹D) formed). The book table on p. 207 reports ε_OH ≈ {0.047, 0.12, 0.23, 0.38} at RH = {10%, 25%, 50%, 80%} respectively — reproduced here at low/moderate RH within ~5% (the book uses the approximate formula ε_OH ≈ 2·k₄·ξ_H₂O/k₃ which diverges at high RH where the k₄·H₂O denominator term becomes non-negligible)."
                        },
                        "P_OH": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                            "description": "OH production rate [m⁻³·s⁻¹] (Eq. 6.3). Product of the O(¹D) source rate j_O₃·O₃ and the OH yield ε_OH: P_OH = j_O₃·O₃·ε_OH. Equivalent to the fully-expanded form 2·j_O₃·O₃·k₄·H₂O / (k₃_eff·M + k₄·H₂O). At S&P p. 207 default conditions P_OH ≈ 1.31e13 m⁻³/s ≈ 1.31e7 molec/cm³/s — the canonical 'OH production rate at 50% RH, 40 ppb O₃, surface' value driving tropospheric OH steady-state concentrations [OH] ≈ P_OH / k_OH_sinks ≈ 1e6-1e7 molec/cm³ that determine the lifetime of CH₄ and other OH-reactive trace gases. Linear in O₃ (via the j_O₃·O₃ factor) and approximately linear in H₂O at low RH (via ε_OH ~ H₂O when k₄·H₂O << k₃_eff·M)."
                        }
                    },
