                "nox": {
                    "variables": {
                        "j_NO2": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "s^-1",
                            "default": 0.008,
                            "description": "NO₂ photolysis rate j_{NO₂} [s⁻¹] for NO₂ + hν → NO + O (λ < 424 nm). The upstream default 8.0e-3 s⁻¹ is the canonical typical-midday surface value (S&P §6.2) — clear-sky, solar zenith angle near noon. j_NO2 is the engine of the whole NOx cycle: it sets the rate of O-atom production (Eq. 6.5) and, together with k_NO_O3, fixes the photostationary-state ozone level (Eq. 6.6). Highly variable in practice — it drops to zero at night, scales with sec(SZA) through the day, and increases with altitude as the overhead O₃ column thins. Overridable for diurnal, seasonal, or altitude scenarios; in the full TroposphericChemistrySystem it is supplied by the upstream FastJX photolysis subsystem via param_to_var coupling."
                        },
                        "k_O_O2_M": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^6/s",
                            "default": 6e-46,
                            "description": "Termolecular rate constant for O + O₂ + M → O₃ + M [m⁶ s⁻¹]. The upstream default is the SI-converted CGS value 6.0e-34 cm⁶ molec⁻² s⁻¹ × 1e-12 (cm⁶→m⁶) = 6.0e-46 m⁶/s (the upstream Julia writes the literal product `6.0e-34 * 1.0e-12`, which evaluates to exactly 6.0e-46 in IEEE-754 Float64). This is the recombination step that converts the O atom from NO₂ photolysis into ozone; it appears only in Eq. 6.5 as part of the O-atom loss denominator k_O_O2_M·[O₂]·[M]. The very large quenching rate k_O_O2_M·[O₂]·[M] ≈ 7.9e4 s⁻¹ at STP makes the ground-state O atom extremely short-lived (~13 µs), which is why Eq. 6.5 is a valid steady-state relation."
                        },
                        "k_NO_O3": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 1.9e-20,
                            "description": "Bimolecular rate constant for NO + O₃ → NO₂ + O₂ [m³ s⁻¹]. The upstream default is the SI-converted CGS value 1.9e-14 cm³ molec⁻¹ s⁻¹ × 1e-6 (cm³→m³) = 1.9e-20 m³/s (S&P p. 211; the upstream Julia writes the literal product `1.9e-14 * 1.0e-6`, exactly 1.9e-20 in Float64). This is the ozone-titration step that closes the NOx cycle by reconverting NO to NO₂. It sets the photostationary-state ozone level (Eq. 6.6: O3_pss ∝ j_NO2/k_NO_O3) and the ozone-loss term of the net production rate (Eq. 6.8). Weakly temperature-dependent in reality (Arrhenius); the upstream uses the temperature-independent ~298 K value for the algebraic system."
                        },
                        "NO": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 2500000000000000.0,
                            "description": "Nitric oxide number density — the `nox` subsystem's NO input. Re-typed from the standalone NOxPhotochemistry component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model NO is governed by the parent coupling equation `nox.NO ~ NO`, which binds it to the combined-system input `NO`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "NO2": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 2.5e+16,
                            "description": "Nitrogen dioxide number density — the `nox` subsystem's NO2 input. Re-typed from the standalone NOxPhotochemistry component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model NO2 is governed by the parent coupling equation `nox.NO2 ~ NO2`, which binds it to the combined-system input `NO2`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "O3": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 1e+18,
                            "description": "Ozone number density — the `nox` subsystem's O3 input. Re-typed from the standalone NOxPhotochemistry component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model O3 is governed by the parent coupling equation `nox.O3 ~ O3`, which binds it to the combined-system input `O3`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "O2": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 5.25e+24,
                            "description": "Molecular oxygen number density — the `nox` subsystem's O2 input. Re-typed from the standalone NOxPhotochemistry component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model O2 is governed by the parent coupling equation `nox.O2 ~ O2`, which binds it to the combined-system input `O2`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "M": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 2.5e+25,
                            "description": "Total air number density number density — the `nox` subsystem's M input. Re-typed from the standalone NOxPhotochemistry component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model M is governed by the parent coupling equation `nox.M ~ M`, which binds it to the combined-system input `M`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "O": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "description": "Ground-state atomic oxygen O(³P) steady-state number density [m⁻³] (Eq. 6.5). Algebraic balance between production from NO₂ photolysis (j_NO2·[NO₂]) and loss by recombination with O₂ (k_O_O2_M·[O₂]·[M]): O = j_NO2·[NO₂] / (k_O_O2_M·[O₂]·[M]). At the typical-midday default conditions O ≈ 5.08e9 m⁻³ — extremely low, because the O atom is consumed within ~13 µs by the fast three-body recombination. The 'steady-state' label reflects the quasi-equilibrium assumption: the O-atom lifetime is far shorter than any other timescale in the cycle, so its concentration tracks the instantaneous NO₂ photolysis rate. Linear in j_NO2 and in [NO₂]; inversely proportional to [O₂] and [M]."
                        },
                        "O3_pss": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "description": "Photostationary-state ozone number density [m⁻³] (Eq. 6.6 — the Leighton relationship). The ozone concentration the NO-NO₂-O₃ cycle would reach in pure photochemical equilibrium: O3_pss = j_NO2·[NO₂] / (k_NO_O3·[NO]). Proportional to the [NO₂]/[NO] ratio and to j_NO2/k_NO_O3. At the typical-midday defaults O3_pss ≈ 8.42e17 m⁻³ (~34 ppb). Independent of the ambient O3 input — O3_pss is what the cycle predicts, not what is measured. In real urban air the measured O3 deviates from O3_pss because peroxy radicals (HO₂, RO₂) provide an extra NO→NO₂ pathway beyond NO + O₃; that deviation is quantified by Φ."
                        },
                        "Φ": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "1",
                            "description": "Photostationary-state parameter Φ, dimensionless (Eq. 6.7). The ratio of the NO₂-photolysis ozone source to the NO+O₃ ozone sink: Φ = j_NO2·[NO₂] / (k_NO_O3·[NO]·[O₃]) = O3_pss/O3. Φ = 1 marks exact photostationary state (pure NO-NO₂-O₃ cycling, no net ozone change). Φ > 1 means the ambient O₃ is below its photostationary value — additional oxidants (HO₂, RO₂ peroxy radicals) are converting NO to NO₂ without consuming O₃, driving net ozone production; typical urban daytime measurements show Φ ≈ 1.5-3. Φ < 1 means ambient O₃ exceeds its PSS value — net ozone loss. At the typical-midday defaults Φ ≈ 0.842 (the default O3 input of 40 ppb sits above the 34 ppb photostationary value)."
                        },
                        "P_O3": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                            "description": "Net ozone production rate [m⁻³ s⁻¹] (Eq. 6.8). The difference between the NO₂-photolysis ozone source and the NO+O₃ ozone sink: P_O3 = j_NO2·[NO₂] − k_NO_O3·[NO]·[O₃]. Positive when the system is below photostationary state (ambient O₃ < O3_pss → net production), negative when above (net loss), and zero at exact PSS — P_O3 and Φ are two views of the same departure from equilibrium (P_O3 = j_NO2·[NO₂]·(1 − 1/Φ)). At the typical-midday defaults P_O3 ≈ -7.5e13 m⁻³/s (net loss, since the default O3 exceeds O3_pss). This is the chemical tendency the NO-NO₂-O₃ cycle alone would impose on ozone; the full tropospheric tendency adds the peroxy-radical channels that NOxPhotochemistry deliberately omits."
                        }
                    },
