                "co": {
                    "variables": {
                        "two": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "1",
                            "default": 2.0,
                            "description": "Stoichiometric factor for the HO₂ self-reaction HO₂ + HO₂ → H₂O₂ + O₂ (S&P §6.3 R6.15): two HO₂ radicals are consumed per reaction event, so the HOx loss contributed by the self-reaction is two·k_HO2_HO2·[HO₂]². Upstream this is an MTK `@constants` entry (default 2, dimensionless); it is preserved here as `type: parameter` with a fixed default of 2.0 so MTK's unit checker sees a named dimensionless quantity rather than a magic literal in the L_HO2 and L_HOx right-hand sides, and so downstream consumers can override the stoichiometric factor for sensitivity studies. The `two_constant_override_sentinel` test overrides it to 1.0 to catch a regression that hard-codes the factor as a literal."
                        },
                        "k_CO_OH": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 2.4e-19,
                            "description": "CO + OH → CO₂ + H rate constant (S&P §6.3 R6.9, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 2.4e-19 m³/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 2.4e-13 cm³/molec/s. This is the chain-initiating step of the CO-oxidation cycle — it consumes CO and an OH radical, producing the H atom that promptly forms HO₂. k_CO_OH appears in the OH loss rate L_OH and (via the CO·OH product) in the high-NOx HO₂ steady state HO2_ss. The clean literal 2.4e-19 differs from the upstream Julia product 2.4e-13·1.0e-6 = 2.3999999999999997e-19 by exactly one ULP (see model reference notes)."
                        },
                        "k_HO2_NO": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 8.1e-18,
                            "description": "HO₂ + NO → OH + NO₂ rate constant (S&P §6.3 R6.11, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 8.1e-18 m³/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 8.1e-12 cm³/molec/s. This is the O₃-producing chain-propagation step: it regenerates OH (sustaining the catalytic HOx cycle) and converts NO to NO₂, whose subsequent photolysis yields an O₃ molecule. k_HO2_NO appears in the HO₂ loss rate L_HO2, the gross O₃-production term of P_O3, the HO₂ steady-state denominator HO2_ss, and the chain_length numerator. The clean literal 8.1e-18 is bit-identical to the upstream Julia product 8.1e-12·1.0e-6."
                        },
                        "k_HO2_HO2": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 2.9e-18,
                            "description": "HO₂ + HO₂ → H₂O₂ + O₂ rate constant (S&P §6.3 R6.15, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 2.9e-18 m³/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 2.9e-12 cm³/molec/s. This is the dominant HOx self-termination channel at low NOx — the HO₂ self-reaction that converts two HO₂ radicals into stable hydrogen peroxide. It enters the HO₂ loss rate L_HO2 and the HOx loss rate L_HOx as the quadratic term two·k_HO2_HO2·[HO₂]² (the factor `two` for the two-HO₂-per-event stoichiometry). The clean literal 2.9e-18 is bit-identical to the upstream Julia product 2.9e-12·1.0e-6."
                        },
                        "k_OH_NO2": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 1e-17,
                            "description": "OH + NO₂ + M → HNO₃ rate constant (S&P §6.3 R6.12, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 1.0e-17 m³/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 1.0e-11 cm³/molec/s. This termolecular reaction is the dominant daytime HOx/NOx termination at high NOx: it removes an OH radical and an NO₂ molecule, converting reactive nitrogen into nitric acid. It enters the OH loss rate L_OH and the HOx loss rate L_HOx. The clean literal 1.0e-17 differs from the upstream Julia product 1.0e-11·1.0e-6 = 9.999999999999999e-18 by exactly one ULP (see model reference notes)."
                        },
                        "k_HO2_O3": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 2e-21,
                            "description": "HO₂ + O₃ → OH + 2O₂ rate constant (S&P §6.3, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 2.0e-21 m³/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 2.0e-15 cm³/molec/s. This is a slow ozone-loss channel — HO₂ reacting directly with ozone — that subtracts from net O₃ production P_O3 and adds to the HO₂ loss rate L_HO2. The clean literal 2.0e-21 differs from the upstream Julia product 2.0e-15·1.0e-6 = 2.0000000000000002e-21 by exactly one ULP (see model reference notes)."
                        },
                        "k_OH_O3": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m^3/s",
                            "default": 7.3e-20,
                            "description": "OH + O₃ → HO₂ + O₂ rate constant (S&P §6.3, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 7.3e-20 m³/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 7.3e-14 cm³/molec/s. This ozone-loss channel — OH reacting with ozone — subtracts from net O₃ production P_O3 and adds to the OH loss rate L_OH. The clean literal 7.3e-20 is bit-identical to the upstream Julia product 7.3e-14·1.0e-6."
                        },
                        "CO": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 2.5e+18,
                            "description": "Carbon monoxide number density — the `co` subsystem's CO input. Re-typed from the standalone COOxidation component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model CO is governed by the parent coupling equation `co.CO ~ CO`, which binds it to the combined-system input `CO`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "OH": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 1000000000000.0,
                            "description": "Hydroxyl radical number density — the `co` subsystem's OH input. Re-typed from the standalone COOxidation component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model OH is governed by the parent coupling equation `co.OH ~ OH`, which binds it to the combined-system input `OH`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "HO2": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 100000000000000.0,
                            "description": "Hydroperoxy radical number density — the `co` subsystem's HO2 input. Re-typed from the standalone COOxidation component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model HO2 is governed by the parent coupling equation `co.HO2 ~ HO2`, which binds it to the combined-system input `HO2`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "NO": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 2500000000000000.0,
                            "description": "Nitric oxide number density — the `co` subsystem's NO input. Re-typed from the standalone COOxidation component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model NO is governed by the parent coupling equation `co.NO ~ NO`, which binds it to the combined-system input `NO`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "NO2": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 2.5e+16,
                            "description": "Nitrogen dioxide number density — the `co` subsystem's NO2 input. Re-typed from the standalone COOxidation component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model NO2 is governed by the parent coupling equation `co.NO2 ~ NO2`, which binds it to the combined-system input `NO2`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "O3": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "default": 1e+18,
                            "description": "Ozone number density — the `co` subsystem's O3 input. Re-typed from the standalone COOxidation component's `parameter` to `state`: in this combined model O3 is governed by the parent coupling equation `co.O3 ~ O3`, which binds it to the combined-system input `O3`. The default is the TypicalConditions value, used only as the nonlinear-solver initial guess."
                        },
                        "P_O3": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                            "description": "Net ozone production rate [m⁻³·s⁻¹] (S&P §6.3, Eqs. 6.9-6.13): P_O3 = k_HO2_NO·HO₂·NO − k_OH_O3·OH·O₃ − k_HO2_O3·HO₂·O₃. The gross production term k_HO2_NO·HO₂·NO counts the O₃ molecules made via HO₂ + NO → OH + NO₂ followed by NO₂ photolysis; the two subtracted terms are the OH+O₃ and HO₂+O₃ ozone-loss channels. At the default scenario P_O3 ≈ 1.752e12 m⁻³·s⁻¹ (net positive — production dominates). P_O3 can go negative when NO is too low to drive much production while O₃ is high (see `upstream_qualitative_low_corner`) or when HO₂ vanishes so only the OH+O₃ loss term survives (see `zero_ho2_net_o3_destruction`)."
                        },
                        "L_HOx": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                            "description": "HOx radical-termination loss rate [m⁻³·s⁻¹] (S&P §6.3, Eqs. 6.11-6.12): L_HOx = k_OH_NO2·OH·NO₂ + two·k_HO2_HO2·HO₂². The two radical-termination channels — OH + NO₂ + M → HNO₃ (the high-NOx NHL channel) and the HO₂ + HO₂ → H₂O₂ self-reaction (the low-NOx HHL channel, carrying the stoichiometric factor `two`). At the default scenario L_HOx ≈ 3.08e11 m⁻³·s⁻¹. L_HOx is the denominator of the HOx chain length: a smaller L_HOx (low NOx, low HO₂) gives a longer catalytic chain."
                        },
                        "L_OH": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                            "description": "OH radical loss rate [m⁻³·s⁻¹] (S&P §6.3, Eq. 6.17 denominator): L_OH = k_CO_OH·CO·OH + k_OH_NO2·OH·NO₂ + k_OH_O3·OH·O₃ — the total rate at which OH is consumed by reaction with CO, with NO₂, and with O₃. At the default scenario L_OH ≈ 9.23e11 m⁻³·s⁻¹. Linear in OH; the OH+CO channel dominates at the default CO=2.5e18 (~100 ppb) loading."
                        },
                        "L_HO2": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                            "description": "HO₂ radical loss rate [m⁻³·s⁻¹] (S&P §6.3): L_HO2 = k_HO2_NO·HO₂·NO + two·k_HO2_HO2·HO₂² + k_HO2_O3·HO₂·O₃ — the total rate at which HO₂ is consumed by reaction with NO, by the HO₂ self-reaction (with the stoichiometric factor `two`), and by reaction with O₃. At the default scenario L_HO2 ≈ 2.283e12 m⁻³·s⁻¹, dominated by the HO₂+NO chain-propagation channel. Quadratic in HO₂ through the self-reaction term, linear in HO₂ through the other two."
                        },
                        "chain_length": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "1",
                            "description": "HOx chain length [dimensionless] (S&P §6.3): chain_length = (k_HO2_NO·HO₂·NO) / L_HOx — the propagation rate of the O₃-producing HO₂ + NO step divided by the HOx termination rate, i.e. the number of OH-HO₂ catalytic cycles a HOx radical completes before it is terminated. The equation references the L_HOx output variable rather than inlining its expression, preserving the upstream symbolic structure. At the default scenario chain_length ≈ 6.575 (a HOx radical drives ~6-7 O₃-producing cycles before termination). chain_length > 1 confirms genuine catalytic cycling; it rises in the low-NOx long-chain regime and falls below 1 in the high-NOx short-chain regime."
                        },
                        "HO2_ss": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m^-3",
                            "description": "HO₂ steady-state concentration in the high-NOx limit [m⁻³] (S&P §6.3 Eq. 6.18): HO2_ss = k_CO_OH·CO·OH / (k_HO2_NO·NO). At high NOx, HO₂ is removed primarily by reaction with NO, so the steady-state HO₂ balances its production from the CO + OH → ... → HO₂ initiation against the HO₂ + NO loss. At the default scenario HO2_ss ≈ 2.963e13 m⁻³. Proportional to CO and OH, inversely proportional to NO; it is a diagnostic estimate independent of the actual HO₂ input used elsewhere in the component."
                        }
                    },
